kes</i> is virtually non-existing in Germany."]},{"name":"Axt","meanings":["German: metonymic occupational name for a woodcutter, carpenter, or maker of axes, from Middle High German <i>ackes</i>, <i>axt-</i> ‘axe’."]}]},{"name":"Henrik","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Henry</b> (  and <b>Heinrich</b> ), especially common in Denmark."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]},{"name":"Busche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Gerhardt, Guenther, Liselotte, Otto.","German: variant (from an inflected form) of   Busch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Busch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Bernd, Hans, Wolfgang, Klaus, Lorenz, Dieter, Erna, Ernst, Helmut, Meinrad.","German (also <b>Büsch</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a thicket or wood, from Middle Low German, Middle High German <i>busch</i> ‘bush, copse’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word or Büsch.","Dutch: variant of   Bosch  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henrik Busche Krummedige af Ottenbüttel was born in 1149, in Steinburg, Schleswig-Holstein, Germany, his father, Hasso Busche Krummedige af Ottenbüttel, was 33 and his mother, Sophie von der Lieth, was 30. He married n.n.. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died after 1209."},"et":{"1149–after 1209":"1149–pärast 1209","1149–